data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Classification

This is **timeout enforcement**: a thread is spawned, `Join(timeout)` waits, and `Thread.Abort()` kills it if time expires. The `ThreadAbortException` catch with `ResetAbort()` is dead-code cleanup logic from Framework.

### Why It Breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 Behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never triggered — no abort is injected |

The timeout path silently **never stops the thread** — it throws `TimeoutException` to the caller while the work continues running indefinitely in the background.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run moves work to the thread pool — no manual thread needed
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            task.WaitAsync(timeout).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // task.Result re-throws wrapped in AggregateException (same as original)
        return task.Result;
    }
}
```

### If the Work Can Cooperate (Preferred)

When you control `work`, accept a `CancellationToken` so the work **actually stops**:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work keeps running** | The non-cooperative version fires-and-forgets the task after timeout. The thread pool thread runs until `work` finishes. This matches the original Framework behavior (abort was best-effort too). |
| **Don't forget `using` on CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | Available on your target (.NET 8). Don't confuse with `Task.Wait(timeout)` which returns `bool` and doesn't throw. |
| **Blocking on async** | `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` keeps the synchronous signature. If you can make callers async, prefer `await` to avoid thread pool starvation. |
| **`AggregateException` wrapping changes** | `task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException` (same as original). `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps to the inner exception. Choose based on your callers' expectations. |

### Validation Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` / `ResetAbort` / `ThreadAbortException`
- ✅ No SYSLIB0006 warnings
- ✅ Timeout still throws `TimeoutException`
- ✅ Exceptions from `work` still surface as `AggregateException`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed (cooperative version)

**Recommendation:** Use the cooperative version whenever you control the work delegate. The non-cooperative version is a drop-in replacement but cannot actually stop runaway work.
